   SOFT-DRINK BOTTLERS' cooperatives upheld by federal
appeals court.
   The Fourth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a lower
court's ruling that a cooperative formed by Coca-Cola
bottlers to make their own plastic bottles doesn't violate
federal antitrust law.
   Sewell Plastics Inc., an Atlanta bottlemaker, had filed
suit in Charlotte, N.C., in 1986 against Coca-Cola Co., 34
Coke bottlers and Southeastern Container Inc., a bottlemaking
cooperative, alleging the cooperative engaged in unfair trade
practices.
   The appeals court ruling, which upheld the lower court's
dismissal of the suit, also allowed a counterclaim against
Sewell to proceed. In the countersuit, Sewell, a unit of
Constar International Inc., Chattanooga, Tenn., is accused of
filing its suit for the improper purpose of trying to force
the bottlers to stop buying from the cooperative and return
to purchasing from Sewell. An attorney for Sewell couldn't be
reached for comment.
   Jonathan Jacobson, an attorney for the defendants, said
the appellate ruling is significant in upholding the rights
of bottlers to form cooperatives.
   Noting that soft-drink bottlers form cooperatives for
various purposes such as buying sugar and making cans, Mr.
Jacobson said an adverse decision would have meant "all the
bottling cooperatives would have been in trouble."
