   LEAN CUISINE ADS were lean on facts about Weight Watchers,
judge rules.
   Weight Watchers International Inc., a unit of H.J. Heinz
Co., had filed a lawsuit accusing Stouffer Corp., which makes
Lean Cuisine frozen foods, of running misleading ads. The
ads, which ran in Parade magazine in 1987 and 1988, promoted
Lean Cuisine dishes as substitutes for Weight Watchers' own
line of diet foods.
   In federal court in Manhattan, Judge Michael Mukasey
ordered Stouffer, a Nestle S.A. subsidiary, not to run the
ads again. The judge ruled that the ads could confuse
consumers into believing that Lean Cuisine is either endorsed
by or related to Weight Watchers. He also ruled that a 1989
ad gave false information comparing Lean Cuisine to Weight
Watchers products.
   Although Judge Mukasey barred Stouffer from resurrecting
the ads, he stopped far short of the action sought by Weight
Watchers. The judge ruled against awarding any damages, and
he said Stouffer couldn't be prohibited from accurately
mentioning Weight Watchers in Lean Cuisine ads.
   A spokesman for Stouffers said the company considers the
decision a victory because it allows Stouffers to promote
Lean Cuisine as an alternative to Weight Watchers' own brand
of low-calorie food. He said the ads, which will begin soon,
will comply with Judge Mukasey's order.
   Weight Watchers had claimed that any use of its name in
the ads would be a trademark infringement.
