   CONNECTICUT MUST NEGOTIATE with an Indian tribe seeking to
open a casino, the Second U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled. The court ruled that Connecticut illegally refused to
discuss the request of the Mashantucket Pequot tribe. The
tribe wants to offer "Las Vegas nights" casino gambling on
its reservation in Ledyard, Conn. Under federal law, the
tribe must reach an agreement with the state before adding
such activities. Connecticut refused to discuss the proposal,
claiming that state law prohibits such games of chance. The
federal appeals-court panel, however, ordered the state to
negotiate in good faith on the request.
   ---
   INTEGRATED RESOURCES INC. received a 60-day extension on
its "exclusivity period," the time in which only it can
officially propose a reorganization plan under Chapter 11 of
the federal Bankruptcy Code. The exclusivity period was to
have expired Sept. 11. Integrated, a former real estate
syndicator that has been operating under bankruptcy-law
protection since February, had sought a 120-day extension
from U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard C. Buschman III, in
New York.
